            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: On Texts and Data</b><br /><br />Descriptions of a universe created for humankind contrast with measurements made in different fields of science.<br /><br />Does that mean ancient epics are wrong?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Literature and Sciences\n\nThere is much confusion around the idea that literature (epics and poems) cannot be related to the sciences.\n\nThis misconception is deepened by the fact that literary texts are often classified imprecisely.\n\nTo help clarify these topics, History Tracers is developing the section *Understanding Texts* (<htcite0>), where we explore in greater depth the relationship between science and literature (<htcite1>), examining, among other things, the boundaries between poetry and fact (<htcite2>).\n\nWhen we restrict ourselves to labeling something as “right” or “wrong,” we often overlook the complexity of texts in favor of convenience or simplicity (<htcite3>; <htcite4>; <htcite5>). A thorough analysis of scientific data and literary works can reveal that both can be correct within their respective contexts.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2806b294-0d2a-4ca2-8008-b2b82791427a",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Understanding texts",
